:''This article is about the NHS hospital in Chertsey, Surrey, England. For the hospital in Hamilton, Ontario, Canada, see [[St Peter's Hospital|St Peter's Hospital, Hamilton]].''

'''St. Peter<U+2019>s Hospital''' is an [[National Health Service (England)|NHS]] district general hospital in [[Chertsey]], [[Surrey]], [[England]]. It has 400 beds and a wide range of acute care services, including an Accident & Emergency department. It is operated by Ashford and St. Peter<U+2019>s Hospital [[NHS Trust]].

St. Peter<U+2019>s Hospital, Chertsey, is situated in {{convert|52|acre|m2}} of [[Green Belt (UK)|Green Belt]] parkland between [[Woking]] and Chertsey near junction 11 of the [[M25 motorway]]. It is {{convert|30|mi|km}} south west of [[central London]] and {{convert|10|mi|km}} from [[Heathrow Airport]]. The main centres of population served by the hospital are Woking, Chertsey, [[Weybridge]], [[Staines]] and [[Walton on Thames]].

Originally St. Peter<U+2019>s Hospital was built to serve casualties of the [[Second World War]]. Over the years, the hospital has been rebuilt, developed and extended to include maternity services, a departmental and clinic area, and a new theatre complex. In the early 1990s, the [[Katharine, The Duchess of Kent|Duchess of Kent]] Wing, which includes a [[Postgraduate Education]] Centre and modern well-equipped wards, was opened. A new building for the Accident & Emergency, [[Intensive care medicine|ITU]] and [[Orthopaedic]] Unit opened in the summer of 1998. In addition, comprehensive HIV and genitourinary medicine services are provided in a dedicated building, the Blanche-Heriot unit.

